In article <rich.768681801@pencil>,
Rich Winkel <rich@pencil.cs.missouri.edu> wrote:
>In <mpjCpLurK.Kxz@netcom.com> mpj@netcom.com (Michael Paul Johnson) writes:
>>The latest freeware Mac version is 2.3 or 2.3aV1.1, depending on the variant.
>>    (Location of the source code for 2.3aV1.1 is a mystery to me).
>
>This is not good.  Any ftp site which carries a compiled version of pgp
>should also have a copy of the corresponding source.

Indeed.  In fact, this is a requirement of the GNU General Public
Licence, under whose terms Phil Zimmerman and others released the
freeware versions of PGP.

> It's not kosher
>to be unable to check the source and demonstrate that it produced the
>compiled file.  Being able to check the source is one of PGP's most
>important security features.

Indeed, and it is a right that it guaranteed to you by the GPL.  Read
the GPL itself for more details (and if you don't have a copy they're
also in violation of it for that, but try lookin in the tarfiles of
any GNU software.)

(Followups redirected out of sci.crypt and alt.privacy.)

